@kthota-g 

After reviewing the current `AgentCard` schema and the discovery mechanism,  I’d like to propose introducing a dedicated schema for agent discovery—separate from the `AgentCard` itself, which I personally see as more closely aligned with agent configuration or even prompt-level semantics rather than discovery metadata.

Instead of relying solely on the agent card being hosted at `/.well-known/agent.json`, I think it could be cleaner to introduce something like a `/.well-known/agents/index.json`, which acts as a registry within the domain and provides a list of available agents, each with metadata like their relative path and a short description. This could follow a new `AgentIndex` schema:

```json
{
  "agents": [
    {
      "path": "/path/to/agent",
      "description": "Does something."
    },
    {
      "path": "/another/agent",
      "description": "Does something else."
    }
  ]
}
```

As for the path structure, I also want to share a few REST-aligned patterns we might consider:

 - `/path/to/agent/agent.json` — used as a sub-resource for retrieving static metadata about the agent, i.e., `AgentCard`.
 - `/path/to/agent` with a GET — returns the `AgentCard` directly (if the endpoint is not used for invocation).
 - `/path/to/agent/card` — an alternative sub-resource that clearly separates metadata from execution.

While (2) and (3) are more REST-idiomatic, I feel (1) is simple and intuitive in practice, especially when the agent is already addressable via `/path/to/agent`. However, there's a risk of redundancy or potential confusion if the agent invocation and metadata paths are too similar or overloaded.

Would love to hear your thoughts on separating discovery from `AgentCard` and whether an `AgentIndex` registry spec might fit into future revisions!

@kthota-g 

In this proposal, I suggest structuring the `AgentIndex` to support both open discovery and entitlement-based agent discovery via a registry, by making either of the following properties mandatory:

1. `agents`:
Used for open discovery, listing publicly available agents. This list does not include entitled agents and only contains information for agents that are discoverable without authorization.
2. `registry_url`:
Used for accessing the agent catalog and entitlement-based discovery via a registry. It allows organizations to manage agent access with finer granularity, such as by role, privilege, and other governance controls.

The `AgentIndex` would allow the flexibility to support both public agents (for open discovery) and authorized agents (for use cases with strict access control) by providing the following structure:

- If `agents` is provided: It serves the purpose of open discovery and only lists public agents.
- If `registry_url` is provided: It enables entitlement-based discovery via a registry and handles access control, such as role-based access or privileges, through **another API specification** that will be defined separately.

This approach keeps the system simple for open discovery while allowing flexibility for more complex scenarios requiring role-based access control:

```json
{
  "title": "AgentIndex",
  "type": "object",
  "description": "Represents a list of agents discoverable under this base URL or via a registry.",
  "properties": {
    "agents": {
      "type": "array",
      "description": "List of publicly available agents for Open Discovery.",
      "items": {
        "$ref": "#/$defs/AgentEntry"
      }
    },
    "registry_url": {
      "type": "string",
      "description": "URL for accessing the agent catalog and entitlement-based discovery via a registry."
    }
  },
  "oneOf": [
    {
      "required": ["agents"]
    },
    {
      "required": ["registry_url"]
    }
  ],
  "$defs": {
    "AgentEntry": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "path": {
          "type": "string",
          "description": "Relative path to the agent metadata (e.g. /path/to/agent/agent.json)"
        },
        "description": {
          "type": "string",
          "description": "Human-readable summary of what the agent does."
        },
        "title": {
          "type": "string",
          "description": "Short name or title for the agent."
        }
      },
      "required": ["path", "title"]
    }
  }
}
```

It would be helpful to get some feedback from the project maintainers 🤔 

@kthota-g 
Are the members of the A2A project currently considering the API design for the Agent Registry/Catalog? Given the nature of the protocol, a Discovery Layer will likely become a necessity.

I implemented a PoC for an Open Discovery API Catalog schema based on the draft specification shared by @darrelmiller. Key points include:

 - Regarding the Registry URL: for clients, it is assumed to be as self-evident as the Remote Agent Base URL (i.e., if a client knows the Remote Agent Base URL, it is also assumed to know the corresponding Registry URL), so it was excluded from the schema.
 - Although the API Catalog schema is still in draft form, it follows the structure outlined in the linked RFC. Wherever possible, I have adopted properties that are commonly used in existing Web Linking practices.
 
```json
 {
    "title": "AgentCatalog",
    "type": "object",
    "description": "Represents a list of agents discoverable under this base URL following the Linkset format.",
    "properties": {
        "linkset": {
            "type": "array",
            "description": "Linkset structure describing agent discovery entries.",
            "items": {
                "$ref": "#/$defs/AgentLinkContext"
            }
        }
    },
    "required": ["linkset"],
    "$defs": {
        "AgentLinkContext": {
            "type": "object",
            "properties": {
                "anchor": {
                    "type": "string",
                    "format": "uri",
                    "description": "Specifies the absolute URI reference that points to an agent endpoint."
                },
                "links": {
                    "type": "array",
                    "description": "List of links associated with the anchor, each describing a discoverable agent card.",
                    "items": {
                        "$ref": "#/$defs/AgentLinkTarget"
                    }
                }
            },
            "required": ["anchor", "links"]
        },
        "AgentLinkTarget": {
            "type": "object",
            "properties": {
                "href": {
                    "type": "string",
                    "format": "uri",
                    "description": "Absolute URI reference to the agent card endpoint."
                },
                "type": {
                    "type": "string",
                    "enum": ["application/json"],
                    "description": "The media type of the linked resource. Must be 'application/json'."
                },
                "rel": {
                    "type": "string",
                    "enum": ["agent-card"],
                    "description": "The relation type of the linked resource. Must be 'agent-card'."
                },
                "name": {
                    "type": "string",
                    "description": "Human-readable name for the agent."
                },
                "description": {
                    "type": "string",
                    "description": "Short description of what this agent does."
                }
            },
            "required": ["href", "type", "rel"]
        }
    }
}
```

For example, if `example.org` is hosting `agent1` and `agent2`, the expected `.well-known/api-catalog.json` would look like the following:

```json
{
  "linkset": [
    {
      "anchor": "https://example.org/agents/agent1/",
      "links": [
        {
          "href": "https://example.org/agents/agent1/agent.json",
          "type": "application/json",
          "rel": "agent-card"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "anchor": "https://example.org/agents/agent2/",
      "links": [
        {
          "href": "https://example.org/agents/agent2/agent.json",
          "type": "application/json",
          "rel": "agent-card"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

If the community finds either the `AgentIndex` schema or the `AgentCatalog` schema reasonable, I’d be happy to consider submitting a PR to include it as an example in the documentation rather than as part of the specification.

Hey @darrelmiller, I have a question regarding the use of extension target attributes in [RFC 9264](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9264#name-extension-target-attributes).

In a JSON Linkset like this:

```json
{
  "linkset": [
    {
      "anchor": "https://example.org/agents/agent1",
      "describedby": [
        {
          "href": "https://example.org/agents/agent1/agent.json",
          "type": "application/json",
          "title": "Agent Card for Agent 1"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

I'd like to add a custom boolean indicator that tells consumers whether the target document is [an extended version of the AgentCard](https://google-a2a.github.io/A2A/specification/#78-agentauthenticatedextendedcard). Based on [Section 4.2.4.3](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9264#name-extension-target-attributes), I’m planning to use an extension target attribute like this:

```json
"extended": ["true"]
```

I understand that:

 - All extension attributes must be serialized as arrays.
 - Values must be JSON strings (since the attribute name does not end with *).

Is this a valid and interoperable way to represent a custom boolean flag using extension attributes in a link target object? Appreciate any feedback or clarification on this usage!

@darrelmiller 

Thanks for the clarification — that makes sense.

You’re absolutely right that without shared agreement, even something that looks like a boolean is just a string in the eyes of the spec. Appreciate the insight!

