In the A2A spec, each agent—regardless of how many skills it supports—exposes a single JSON-RPC endpoint and communicates using a standardized set of methods like task/send, task/subscribe, etc. You won't see custom method names like route.plan or map.custom—instead, all interactions come through task/send, and the skill intent is implicitly embedded in the message/part field.

So how does the agent know whether it should find a route or generate a map?

That’s where intelligent routing comes into play. A capable agent with multiple skills will usually do one of the following:

Use a single LLM model with a composable system prompt that describes all its capabilities (like the agent card).

Leverage internal routing logic or a dispatcher (which could itself be AI-powered) to parse the message/part field and determine the appropriate skill (e.g., custom-map-generator vs route-optimizer-traffic).

In terms of code, the architecture typically looks like this:

Agent receives a task/send JSON-RPC call at a single endpoint.

The message/text (or JSON structure) is passed through a skill selector—this could be a set of rules, tags, or a prompt sent to an LLM.

Based on the determined skill, the request is routed to the corresponding internal handler/function/class.

The response is then sent back in the A2A-compatible format.

