Hey! Thanks for the great question. Currently, my implementation focuses on role-based filtering at the `/.well-known/agent.json` endpoint, as that's where most clients interact. While I haven't explicitly implemented the `/agent/authenticatedExtendedCard` endpoint yet, my current architecture demonstrates the core concepts that would make this extension natural and powerful. Here's my practical experience with role-based agent card filtering:

## Current Implementation

```java
@Agent(groupName = "car booking")
public class CarBookingAgent {
    @PreAuthorize("hasRole('USER')")
    @Action(description = "Book a car")
    public String bookCar(/*...*/) { /*...*/ }

    @PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')")
    @Action(description = "Cancel a booking")
    public String cancelCarBooking(/*...*/) { /*...*/ }
}
```

In my current implementation, when different roles access the `/.well-known/agent.json` endpoint, they get different views of the agent's capabilities (which could be easily extended to the `/agent/authenticatedExtendedCard` endpoint):

1. **USER Role Gets:**
   ```json
   {
     "skills": [
       {
         "id": "bookCar",
         "name": "Book Car",
         "description": "Book a car for rental"
       },
       {
         "id": "getBookingStatus",
         "name": "Get Status",
         "description": "Check booking status"
       }
     ]
   }
   ```

2. **ADMIN Role Gets:**
   ```json
   {
     "skills": [
       // All USER skills plus:
       {
         "id": "cancelCarBooking",
         "name": "Cancel Booking",
         "description": "Cancel an existing booking"
       },
       {
         "id": "generateReport",
         "name": "Generate Report",
         "description": "Generate booking reports"
       }
     ]
   }
   ```

## Suggested Specification Enhancements

I think we could enhance the specification in these areas:

1. **Role-Based Skill Filtering**
   ```typescript
   interface AgentCard {
     // ...existing fields...
     securityContext?: {
       roleBasedFiltering: boolean;
       supportedRoles: string[];
     }
   }
   ```

2. **Skill-Level Security Metadata**
   ```typescript
   interface Skill {
     // ...existing fields...
     security?: {
       requiredRoles: string[];
       requiredPermissions: string[];
     }
   }
   ```

3. **Version Tracking for Role-Specific Cards**
   ```typescript
   interface AgentCard {
     // ...existing fields...
     roleSpecificVersion?: string; // Version specific to role combination
   }
   ```

## Current Implementation & Future Extension

1. **Current Approach**
   ```java
   @GetMapping("/.well-known/agent.json")
   public AgentCard getAgentCard(Authentication auth) {
       Set<String> roles = (auth != null) 
           ? auth.getAuthorities()
               .stream()
               .map(GrantedAuthority::getAuthority)
               .collect(Collectors.toSet())
           : Collections.emptySet();
           
       return agentCardGenerator.generateForRoles(roles);
   }
   ```

2. **Planned Extension for authenticatedExtendedCard**
   - Will maintain MCP compatibility
   - Extend current role-based filtering
   - Add support for more detailed capability exposure
   - Implement proper caching with role-specific versions

3. **Performance Optimization**
   - Pre-compute common role combinations
   - Cache role-specific card versions
   - Use lazy loading for large skill sets

You can see a working example in my [A2A-MCP-Security demo](https://vishalmysore-a2amcpdemo.hf.space/index.html).

## Benefits of This Approach

1. **Clean Separation of Concerns**
   - Security logic stays in annotations
   - Card generation respects security context
   - Easy to maintain and extend

2. **Flexible Authorization**
   - Supports both RBAC and ABAC
   - Can handle complex permission combinations
   - Works with custom security rules

3. **Better Client Experience**
   - Clients see only what they can access
   - Reduced need for error handling
   - Clearer capability boundaries

While I haven't implemented the `/agent/authenticatedExtendedCard` endpoint yet (as current clients primarily use `/.well-known/agent.json`), I'm will be  evolving this implementation as client support grows. The suggested specification enhancements could work well for both endpoints while maintaining compatibility with the MCP specification.

Would love to hear thoughts on these suggestions and discuss how we can best support both A2A and MCP clients as they adopt authenticated RBAC based actions!

hi  guys, here let me introduce a2a4j, which is the Java version of the a2a protocol. 😊 https://github.com/a2ap/a2a4j

[A2A4J](https://github.com/a2ap/a2a4j) is a comprehensive Java implementation of the Agent2Agent (A2A) Protocol, providing an open standard for communication and interoperability between independent AI agent systems. Built with Spring Boot integration and reactive programming support, A2A4J enables agents to discover each other's capabilities, collaborate on tasks, and securely exchange information without needing access to each other's internal state.

This project is still in its early stages and is currently maintained by three team members who are very interested in the A2A protocol.

We hope to release an version as soon as possible.

## 🚀 Features

- ✅ **Complete A2A Protocol Support** - Full implementation of the Agent2Agent specification
- ✅ **JSON-RPC 2.0 Communication** - Standards-based request/response messaging
- ✅ **Server-Sent Events Streaming** - Real-time task updates and streaming responses
- ✅ **Task Lifecycle Management** - Comprehensive task state management and monitoring
- ✅ **Spring Boot Integration** - Easy integration with Spring Boot applications
- ✅ **Reactive Programming Support** - Built on Reactor for scalable, non-blocking operations
- ✅ **Multiple Content Types** - Support for text, files, and structured data exchange
- ⚪️ **Agent Card Discovery** - Dynamic capability discovery mechanism
- ⚪️ **Push Notification Configuration** - Asynchronous task updates via webhooks
- ⚪️ **Enterprise Security** - Authentication and authorization support


## 🏗️ Project Structure

```
a2a4j/
├── a2a4j-core/                    # Core A2A protocol implementation
├── a2a4j-spring-boot-starter/     # Spring Boot auto-configuration
│   ├── a2a4j-server-spring-boot-starter/   # Server-side starter
│   └── a2a4j-client-spring-boot-starter/   # Client-side starter
├── a2a4j-samples/                 # Example implementations
│   └── server-hello-world/        # Hello World server example
├── specification/                 # A2A protocol specification
├── tools/                        # Development tools and configuration
```


## 🔧 Usage Examples

### Creating an A2A Server

```java
@RestController
public class MyA2AController {

    @Autowired
    private A2AServer a2aServer;
    @Autowired
    private final Dispatcher a2aDispatch;

    @GetMapping(".well-known/agent.json")
    public ResponseEntity<AgentCard> getAgentCard() {
        AgentCard card = a2aServer.getSelfAgentCard();
        return ResponseEntity.ok(card);
    }

    @PostMapping(value = "/a2a/server", produces = MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON_VALUE)
    public ResponseEntity<JSONRPCResponse> handleA2ARequestTask(@RequestBody JSONRPCRequest request) {
        return ResponseEntity.ok(a2aDispatch.dispatch(request));
    }

    @PostMapping(value = "/a2a/server", produces = MediaType.TEXT_EVENT_STREAM_VALUE)
    public Flux<ServerSentEvent<JSONRPCResponse>> handleA2ARequestTaskSubscribe(@RequestBody JSONRPCRequest request) {
        return a2aDispatch.dispatchStream(request).map(event -> ServerSentEvent.<JSONRPCResponse>builder()
                .data(event).event("task-update").build());
    }
}

@Component
public class MyAgentExecutor implements AgentExecutor {

    @Override
    public Mono<Void> execute(RequestContext context, EventQueue eventQueue) {
        // your agent logic code
        TaskStatusUpdateEvent completedEvent = TaskStatusUpdateEvent.builder()
                .taskId(taskId)
                .contextId(contextId)
                .status(TaskStatus.builder()
                        .state(TaskState.COMPLETED)
                        .timestamp(String.valueOf(Instant.now().toEpochMilli()))
                        .message(createAgentMessage("Task completed successfully! Hi you."))
                        .build())
                .isFinal(true)
                .metadata(Map.of(
                        "executionTime", "3000ms",
                        "artifactsGenerated", 4,
                        "success", true))
                .build();

        eventQueue.enqueueEvent(completedEvent);
        return Mono.empty();
    }
}
```


