Hey A2A community! 👋 I'm excited to share my experience integrating Apache Thrift with A2A (Agent-to-Agent) and MCP (Model Context Protocol) to build a high-performance, polyglot AI agent mesh. This combination could be  excellent for our distributed AI systems.

## Why This Matters 🎯

Many of us are building AI systems that need to:
- Connect agents written in different languages
- Handle high-throughput model inference
- Maintain low latency for real-time AI
- Scale across distributed environments

## The Power of Thrift + A2A/MCP 💪

Here's a quick example of how elegant this integration can be:

```java
@Agent(name = "WeatherAgent")
public class WeatherServiceA2A implements WeatherService.Iface {
    @Action(description = "Get AI-powered weather forecast")
    @Override
    public String getForecast(String city) {
        // Seamlessly delegate to Python AI model
        try (ThriftClient<WeatherService.Client> client = pythonClientPool.acquire()) {
            return client.get().getForecast(city);
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Benefits  📈

1. **Cross-Language AI Integration**
   - Python for ML models
   - Java/Scala for enterprise services
   - C++ for performance-critical components
   - All communicating seamlessly!

2. **Performance Gains**
   - Binary protocol = smaller payloads
   - Direct TCP connections = lower latency
   - Type safety across languages
   - Efficient tensor/model weight transfer

3. **A2A/MCP Integration**
   - Natural fit with A2A's agent discovery
   - MCP tools exposed across languages
   - Protocol translation built-in
   - Unified agent mesh topology


## Quick Implementation Guide 🛠️

1. Define your Thrift interface:
```thrift
service AIService {
    binary performInference(1: binary inputTensor)
    map<string, double> getModelMetrics()
}
```

2. Implement A2A agent with Thrift:
```java
@Agent(groupName = "AI Services")
public class AIServiceAgent implements AIService.Iface {
    @Action(description = "Run model inference")
    public byte[] performInference(byte[] inputTensor) {
        // Your implementation here
    }
}
```

3. Register as MCP tool:
```java
@MCPTool(name = "model_inference")
public class ModelInferenceTool {
    private final AIServiceAgent agent;
    
    public MCPResponse execute(MCPRequest request) {
        byte[] tensor = prepareTensor(request);
        return translateToMCP(agent.performInference(tensor));
    }
}
```


## Getting Started 🚀

Check out our complete example on GitHub: [a2aThriftExample](https://github.com/vishalmysore/mcp-apache-thrift)


## Feedback! 💭

