Totally agree with this. Semantic matching for payload alignment is fragile.I actually come from telecom and this is a solved problem in that world. SIP uses something called the SDP Offer/Answer model (RFC 3264) for exactly this. When two endpoints connect, the caller says `here's what I support `codecs, media types, bitrates. The callee picks from that list. No overlap? Clean failure. Either side can renegotiate mid-session.
What you're describing maps almost directly to this pattern. Applied to A2A, it could look something like:
Agent A (offer):
```
{
  "context_available": {
    "conversation_turns": 47,
    "tool_results": 3,
    "formats": ["full_history", "summary", "structured_state"],
    "total_tokens": 24000,
    "pii_present": true
  }
}
```
Agent B (answer):
```json
{
  "context_accepted": {
    "format": "structured_state",
    "max_tokens": 8000,
    "require_pii_redaction": true
  }
}
```

Both sides agree on exactly what gets exchanged before anything moves. No guessing. Version the schema and you get the deterministic interface management you're talking about for enterprise. I think it complements the existing skills system nicely; skills describe what an agent can do, this handles how they actually exchange data.

